node.text: Photo by Trần Tuấn Việt @vietsui / A man walks under one of the giant trees named Thần Nông ("god of agriculture") in Song Lo District, Vinh Phuc Province, Vietnam. The two Bombax ceiba trees are more than 300 years old and were recognized as Vietnam Heritage Trees in 2016. The Bombax ceiba tree is considered one of the symbols of the Vietnamese countryside. #YourShotPhotographer #Vietnam

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by National Geographic Your Shot on September 13, 2021. May be an image of body of water and nature.

node.text: Photo by Derek Morf @_morfoto_ / Visiting Bruarfoss waterfall in Iceland can be hit or miss, depending on the rains. Too much rain and the falls are completely transformed into a brown flood of water, with no glacial blues to be found. Visit at just the right time, though, and it can be stunning. This is an Editor’s Pick chosen from #YourShotPhotographer. Submit your photos for a chance to be featured on the account!

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by National Geographic Your Shot on September 13, 2021.

node.text:
Photos by Juan Carlos Osorio @juancosoriophotography / 9/11 Tribute in Light / I took these images after sunset on September 11, 2021, the 20th anniversary of the attack and destruction of the Twin Towers at the World Trade Center. September 11, 2001, was one of the darkest days in our history; 2,996 people lost their lives. Even after 20 years, some remains are still being identified through advanced DNA testing, bringing closure to relatives while also reopening wounds. These twin beams of light are comprised of 88 7,000-watt xenon light bulbs that can reach four miles (six kilometers) up in the sky and can be seen on a clear night like this from 60 miles (97 kilometers) away.
We will never forget. The world will never forget. The lives of the victims will reach far and wide, just as the lights that pay them tribute.
For these and more images about people, nature, travel, and wildlife, visit @juancosoriophotography. #YourShotPhotographer #911memorial #neverforget #September11 #NewYorkCity

node.text: Photo by @taylorthomasalbright / Towering, snow-covered mountains surround this meadow in Lake Clark. During the early summer months, many bears gather here to mate and feed on the protein-rich sedge grass. #YourShotPhotographer

node.text: Photo by Laura Gregory @LauraLynPhotography / It's getting to be the time of year for the rut. The tundra lights up in reds, pinks, oranges, and yellows. Bull moose lose their felt and display new bony racks, which they use to showcase their dominancy and attract cow moose. #YourShotPhotographer #DenaliNationalPark #Moose

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by National Geographic Your Shot on September 12, 2021. May be an image of wading bird, nature and body of water.

node.text: Photo by Emilie Reid @Emilie.Reid.Photographie / A Snowy Egret at Dawn just about to take off. Taken on Hilton Head Island, South Carolina. Due to a lack of motivation, summertime depression, and an overall loss of interest in my photography, I hadn't been to the beach to photograph in a long time. On this particular morning, there was an incredible sunrise, with beautiful colors and low clouds, providing an epic sky, and not only that, but there were about 50 Snowy Egrets gathered together fishing. It was an incredible experience! The bird photographed was one of many that I witnessed that special morning, a morning that reminded me of the deep connection that I have with nature and the joy and serenity that my time with the birds brings to me. This is an Editor’s Pick chosen from #YourShotPhotographer. Submit your photos for a chance to be featured on the account!

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by National Geographic Your Shot on September 10, 2021. May be an image of nature and sky.

node.text: Photo by @navidbaraty / The Milky Way rises over the otherworldly limestone tufas and foliage of Mono Lake in California. The lake is one of the most hauntingly beautiful places I've ever photographed at night. This was a 25-second exposure, and I briefly illuminated the foreground elements with a low-luminosity light during the exposure. #YourShotPhotographer #MonoLake #nightsky #twanight

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by National Geographic Your Shot on September 10, 2021. May be an image of bird and nature.

node.text: Photo by @sarmistha_bera / Chaotic Canvas / This is the view of Mullick Ghat near the iconic Howrah Bridge in Kolkata, India. There are many people in this frame: Some are taking a bath, some are worshipping the river, some are getting a haircut, and some are indulged in other chores. Each of them seems to have a story of their own. Since the flower market is near this ghat, many people are washing flowers before going to the market. #YourShotPhotographer #kolkata #streetphotography

node.text: Photo by Gustav Parenmark @macrogp / A great green bush-cricket (Tettigonia viridissima) staring in to the camera with its compound eyes on the island of Fårö, Sweden. This is a composite image comprised of 17 images at different focal lengths stacked on top of each other. This is an Editor’s Pick chosen from #YourShotPhotographer. Submit your photos for a chance to be featured on the account!

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by National Geographic Your Shot on September 10, 2021. May be an image of bird and nature.

node.text:
Photo and video by @gretchenkaystuart / Swipe and turn the volume up to hear the mating call of the male sooty grouse (along with the sounds of other birds and waterfalls). This noise is probably my favorite thing about spring in Mount Rainier. As low and subtle as his call is, it travels a surprisingly long distance and adds so beautifully to the enchantment of the forest. 
Image and video were captured handheld with a long lens and cropped, giving the sooty grouse plenty of space as to not interrupt his natural behavior. #sootygrouse #mountrainier #YourShotPhotographer
